  83 |     Each validation point counts equally in the aggregate reward. Datasets with
  84 |     more held-out validation curves therefore contribute proportionally more:
  85 | 
  86 |         per_dataset_loss = dataset_nmse
  87 |         scored_nmse = sum(per_dataset_loss * n_val_points) / sum(n_val_points)
  88 | 
  89 |     Hard-case datasets are still reported in evaluator feedback so you can
  90 |     target outliers. Higher `combined_score` then applies a bounded 20% parsimony penalty for
  91 |     more complex expressions:
  92 | 
  93 |         fit_score = 1 / (1 + scored_nmse)
  94 |         combined_score = fit_score * parsimony_penalty_factor
  95 | 
  96 |     A candidate that fails on any dataset is penalized heavily, so robustness
  97 |     across all datasets matters more than a strong fit on a subset. Simplicity
  98 |     is a secondary objective: do not sacrifice a meaningful fit improvement for
  99 |     a tiny reduction in complexity, but prefer the simpler expression when two
 100 |     candidates are close.
 101 | 
 102 |     Keep the equation structure as simple as possible. We do not want to overfit to the data. We want to find a general equation that works for all datasets. It is not preferable to come up with a very complex equation. We want a general governing law
 103 | 
 104 |     ## Focused agentic workflow
 105 |     Keep exploration short and bounded. You already know the benchmark layout,
 106 |     evaluator contract, and `pysr_harness` API from this prompt; do not spend
 107 |     many turns rediscovering them.
 108 | 
 109 |     Use tools when they provide information that materially improves the next
 110 |     candidate. Keep exploration purposeful and bounded: prefer targeted reads,
 111 |     searches, or paper lookups over broad discovery.
 112 | 
 113 |     Internet and paper tools are available and valuable for this task. When the
 114 |     run history shows stalled progress, repeated regressions, or uncertainty
 115 |     about the right structure, do not simply remix the current expression.
 116 |     Perform targeted research into governing relationships, empirical response
 117 |     shapes, scaling behavior, or robustness principles that may apply to this
 118 |     kind of data. Avoid copying a named formula blindly; extract the structural
 119 |     principle that makes it useful, then express that principle as one compact,
 120 |     stable symbolic template.
 121 | 
 122 |     If recent run history or traces show no external research yet, make at
 123 |     least one targeted `web_search` or `research_papers` call before finalizing
 124 |     your next candidate. If the tool returns no useful results or fails, say so
 125 |     briefly in your reasoning and continue from local evidence.
 126 | 
 127 |     Before every `run_command`, silently do this checklist:
 128 |     - Expected runtime under 10 seconds?
 129 |     - Expected output under 80 lines?
 130 |     - Uses only a known path from the prompt/repo map?
 131 |     - Avoids shell-only syntax?
 132 |     If any answer is "no", do not run the command.
 133 | 
 134 |     Never run filesystem discovery commands (`find`, broad `ls`, recursive
 135 |     scans, `/`, `/home`, `/usr`, `/opt`, or whole-repo searches). Never use
 136 |     shell metacharacters in safe-mode commands: no pipes (`|`), redirects
 137 |     (`>`, `2>/dev/null`), command chaining (`&&`, `;`), globs intended for the
 138 |     shell, or `head`/`tail` pipelines. Use only short Python snippets over known
 139 |     files, with explicit bounded printing.
 140 | 
 141 |     Do not dump full source files, full dataset listings, long per-dataset
 142 |     tables, or warning-heavy experiment transcripts into the conversation. If
 143 |     you test a model, test at most 3 representative datasets and print only one
 144 |     aggregate score plus at most 3 hard-case lines.
 145 | 
 146 |     If `read_file` says a path is outside the codebase root, do not spend more
 147 |     tool calls trying to rediscover that file. Use the API description in this
 148 |     prompt and output a complete candidate. Failed exploration is a signal to
 149 |     stop exploring, not to search more broadly.
 150 | 
 151 |     Stop exploring once you have a plausible, well-justified improvement.
 152 |     Output the complete improved EVOLVE-BLOCK program instead of running many
 153 |     variants. Repeated local experiments are worse than a concise, robust
 154 |     candidate.
 155 | 
 156 |     ## Optional Run History
 157 |     The AdaEvolve prompt may include a live run-progress section showing the
 158 |     current iteration, the requested run window, and remaining iterations. Use
 159 |     that progress signal to decide whether to exploit a promising direction or
 160 |     explore a different structure before the run budget is exhausted.
 161 | 
 162 |     If a visible run-history snapshot exists, you may inspect it to avoid
 163 |     repeating recently tried ideas. Use only the bounded files you need:
 164 |     - `reference/current_adaevolve_run/run_history_summary.json`
 165 |     - `reference/current_adaevolve_run/adaevolve_iteration_stats.jsonl`
 166 |     - `reference/current_adaevolve_run/checkpoints/`
 167 |     - `reference/agentic_trace_*.json`
 168 | 
 169 |     Treat this snapshot as context, not as a target to copy. Prefer the summary
 170 |     first; only read individual checkpoint programs when you need to understand
 171 |     a specific prior candidate. Use recent agentic traces only when you need to
 172 |     understand which tool calls, research paths, or reasoning steps led to the
 173 |     previous candidate.
 174 | 
 175 |     When reading iteration stats, distinguish the fields carefully:
 176 |     - `global.global_best_score` is the best score found up to and including
 177 |       that iteration.
 178 |     - `global.current_iteration_best_score` is the best score among programs
 179 |       produced in that specific iteration.
 180 |     - `iteration_result.child_program.metrics.combined_score` is the score of
 181 |       the newly generated child for that iteration.
 182 |     - A plateau means the child scores are failing to exceed the running best
 183 |       for several iterations, even if `global_best_score` remains high.
 184 | 
 185 |     ## Task
 186 |     Improve the `evaluate_symbolic_candidate()` function in the EVOLVE-BLOCK.
 187 |     Build an explicit symbolic expression template using the `pysr_harness` API.
 188 | 
 189 |     Use `pysr_harness.equation_session` helpers:
 190 |     - `feature_symbols(n)` → PySR variables `x0`, `x1`, ...
 191 |       Here x0 is normalized time and x1 is the experimental parameter.
 192 |     - `constant_symbols(n)` → tunable constants `c0`, `c1`, ...
 193 |     - `evaluate_expression(expr, X_train, y_train, X_val, y_val, constants=...)`
 194 |       fits constants via least-squares and returns scored metrics.
 195 | 
 196 |     ## Search Strategy
 197 |     Do not assume a particular equation family. Use the current candidate,
 198 |     prior scores, evaluator feedback, and any bounded diagnostics you choose
 199 |     to inspect to infer what structural change is justified.
 200 | 
 201 |     Understand exploration vs exploitation in this evolutionary search:
 202 |     - Exploration means deliberately moving to a different structural region
 203 |       when local mutations are not improving the running best. Use it to test
 204 |       a new principle, transformation, variable interaction, or stability idea.
 205 |       Exploration should still be disciplined: explain what failure mode or
 206 |       hypothesis the new structure targets.
 207 |     - Exploitation means refining a promising family after it shows improvement.
 208 |       Use it for small, controlled changes that preserve the useful behavior
 209 |       while addressing a clear limitation such as scaling, baseline behavior,
 210 |       numerical conditioning, or unnecessary complexity.
 211 |     - If recent child scores regress or duplicate the current best, switch from
 212 |       incremental tweaks to evidence gathering. Inspect run history, hard cases,
 213 |       and, when useful, external sources before proposing the next expression.
 214 |     - If a child improves substantially, exploit that direction with minimal
 215 |       changes rather than immediately replacing the whole structure.
 216 | 
 217 |     Before changing the expression, identify the most likely limitation:
 218 |     - poor fit quality on many datasets
 219 |     - non-finite predictions or invalid arithmetic on one or more datasets
 220 |     - excessive sensitivity to x0 or x1 scaling
 221 |     - over-parameterization that makes constant fitting unreliable
 222 |     - under-parameterization that cannot capture shared structure
 223 |     - a redundant term that adds complexity without improving robustness
 224 | 
 225 |     Prefer the smallest structural change that targets the limitation you
 226 |     identify. Do not add complexity merely because more constants are allowed.
 227 |     Because complexity has a small direct score penalty, every extra operation
 228 |     or fitted constant should have a clear expected payoff in validation fit or
 229 |     robustness.
 230 | 
 231 |     Good candidates are:
 232 |     - smooth and globally defined over the observed x0 and x1 ranges
 233 |     - numerically stable during least-squares fitting
 234 |     - compact enough for reliable optimization from one initial point
 235 |     - able to use x1 when it is informative without depending on it too strongly
 236 |     - robust on small, noisy, or unusually scaled datasets
 237 | 
 238 |     Be especially cautious with operations that can create singularities,
 239 |     non-real values, overflow, or invalid powers during fitting. If you use
 240 |     division, exponentials, logarithms, square roots, or variable exponents,
 241 |     explain why the resulting expression remains well behaved.
 242 | 
 243 |     Keep the number of fitted constants moderate. Too many constants risk
 244 |     unstable fits on small datasets; too few can underfit shared structure.
 245 | 
 246 |     ## Constraints
 247 |     - Exactly one call to `evaluate_expression(...)` per
 248 |       `evaluate_symbolic_candidate()` invocation.
 249 |     - Directly `return evaluate_expression(...)`; do not assign the result to a
 250 |       variable, edit it, wrap it, or post-process it.
 251 |     - The `equation_template` returned by the scorer must be identical for every
 252 |       dataset; only fitted constant values may differ across datasets.
 253 |     - Keep `evaluate_symbolic_candidate()` straight-line: no loops, conditionals,
 254 |       try/except blocks, nested functions/classes, comprehensions, helper
 255 |       function calls, or imports inside the function.
 256 |     - Do not use `Piecewise`, `Max`, `Min`, `sign`, `floor`, `ceiling`,
 257 |       `Heaviside`, relational/boolean expressions, or other gated/conditional
 258 |       symbolic constructs.
 259 |     - Keep symbolic complexity under 160 nodes and fitted constants under 13.
 260 |     - Do NOT call PySRRegressor.fit, run_gp_session, or equation_search.
 261 |     - Do NOT implement multiple candidate templates and choose the one with the
 262 |       lowest loss.
 263 |     - Keep expressions numerically stable and general.
 264 |     - Do not hardcode data values or indices.
 265 |     - Keep runtime reasonable (3000s timeout for all datasets combined).
